        "content": "<p>Hi all. A quick question, if you don't mind. I appreciate that Lean supports dot notation, but it seems like you'd have to use nested parentheses if you wanted to chain dot notation function calls.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(((</span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">7</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is there another way to use dot notation that doesn't require nesting parentheses like this, or is dot notation in Lean not really meant for chaining?</p>\n<p>Thanks.</p>",
        "id": 508981536,
        "sender_full_name": "misterdrgn",
        "timestamp": 1743302226
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>check this out:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">7</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 508981843,
        "sender_full_name": "Matt Diamond",
        "timestamp": 1743302468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"380294\">Matt Diamond</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Chaining.20dot.20notation/near/508981843\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>check this out:</p>\n<p><div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">6</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">|&gt;.</span><span class=\"n\">add</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">7</span>\n</code></pre></div><br>\n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ah, nice. And if you mouse over the <code>|&gt;.</code>, it tells you exactly what it does and why.</p>",
